I've always questioned why we can't counter-sue people for clumsiness.<br>
<br>
If five thousand people walk down my sidewalk per year and one person trips, I would posit that the person who tripped by definition has a proclivity to tripping.  Why should I be held responsible for this?<br>
<br>
What happened to the concept of personal responsibility anyway?   I mean, why can't Micky Dees sue the broad who spilled the coffee for being an idiot?   There is ALWAYS assumed risk in anything that you do.  If you drive and drink coffee in the car, you assumed some risk.  You also increase your risk of getting in an accident.<br>
<br>
Suppose, instead of spilling it on herself, she dropped the coffee and it harmlessly fell on the passenger seat, yet was spilling onto the cloth.  She reaches over to pick up the cup, takes her eyes off the road, and slams her car into a bridge abutment and gets decapitated.   Who's fault is it now?   If it were caught on video tape, there'd probably be a law now that drive-thru's are illegal and some snake lawyer would be negotiating on his second yacht.<br>
<br>
I think there needs to be some legislation put into effect that essentially states. &quot;If you are NOT encapsulated in a steel capsule in a geologically stable region with food, supplies, sewage and air that will last your lifetime then you assume risk doing anything.   If you chose not to accept these risks, please enter your capsule post haste as no one is going to pay your for your own stupidity&quot;<br>
<br>
-Mal<br>
